The animation will not display the orange rectangle at every pixel in the path due to Android&#39;s finite frame rate. You may see the rectangle displayed at each pixel for some very specific circumstances, but that will generally not be the case.

Here is what I suggest:

1. Divide the animation into three segments: the first from the start position to the right edge of the green rectangle; the second from the right edge of the green rectangle to the left edge of the green rectangle, and the third from the left edge of the green rectangle to the left end of the animation. You can chain these animations together.

2. If the user clicks the button during the animation that is running in the middle, then it is a &quot;hit&quot;, otherwise, it is a &quot;miss.&quot;

By doing it this way, it won&#39;t matter how the orange rectangle gets to the center - skipping pixels or even skipping frames.

You can modify the start and stop position of the middle animation to fine tune it if you want such as making the middle animation much smaller if you want the user to try for the center of the green rectangle.

---
---

I put together a small app that demonstrates splitting the animation into three segments and three separate animations that look like one animation. (See below.) To do this, I had to use a [LinearInterpolator](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/view/animation/LinearInterpolator) to make the transition seamless. 

You can try this code out to see if it helps you - it may or may not. You will still be limited by the frame rate of the device (60fps, 90fps, 120fps). This means, that for any length of movement beyond the shortest length, the app will skip pixels. For instance, moving a view 1,000 pixels in 2 seconds for a 60 fps device will show the view 120 times at 8.3 pixel increments (8.3 = 1,000/(2x60)). This assumes a fast device and an excution environment that is not too busy. If the device/emulator is slow or the environment is busy, you will see a varying number of varying gap sizes in the movement.

You may want to look at [SurfaceView](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/view/SurfaceView) for drawing the game. I don&#39;t have any real experience with it, but it seems to be used in games and may give you better results. It will get the app off of the main thread and will avoid much the the Android view system that can be slow.

Here is the code:

	public class Test2 extends Fragment implements View.OnTouchListener {
	    private FragmentTestBinding binding;

	    // Assume moving rectangle moves from initial position to x = 0.
	    private float moving_rectangle_full_shift = 0f;

	    // The full shift is composed of three shifts
	    private float moving_rectangle_shift_1 = 0f;
	    private float moving_rectangle_shift_2 = 0f;
	    private float moving_rectangle_shift_3 = 0f;

	    private final long moving_rectangle_full_shift_duration = 2000L;

	    // Each shift will last for a duration proportional to is size relative to the full shift.
	    // This assumes a linear interpolator for the animation.
	    private long moving_rectangle_shift_1_duration = 0L;
	    private long moving_rectangle_shift_2_duration = 0L;
	    private long moving_rectangle_shift_3_duration = 0L;

	    // Set to chain the three animations together.
	    private final AnimatorSet animatorSet = new AnimatorSet();

	    private float lastTransX = 0f;
	    private int frameCount = 0;

	    public Test2() {
	    }

	    @SuppressLint(&quot;ClickableViewAccessibility&quot;)
	    @Override
	    public View onCreateView(@NonNull LayoutInflater inflater, ViewGroup container,
	                             Bundle savedInstanceState) {
	        binding = DataBindingUtil.setContentView(requireActivity(), R.layout.fragment_test);
	        binding.buttonAction.setOnTouchListener(this);
	        binding.getRoot().addOnLayoutChangeListener(new View.OnLayoutChangeListener() {
	            @Override
	            public void onLayoutChange(View v, int left, int top, int right, int bottom,
	                                       int oldLeft, int oldTop, int oldRight, int oldBottom) {
	                binding.getRoot().removeOnLayoutChangeListener(this);
	                Log.d(&quot;Applog&quot;, String.format(&quot;Target between %d and %d&quot;,
	                        binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getLeft()
	                                - binding.movingRectangle.getLeft(),
	                        binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getLeft() -
	                                binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getRight()));

	                moving_rectangle_full_shift = -binding.movingRectangle.getX();
	                moving_rectangle_shift_1 = -(-moving_rectangle_full_shift
	                        - binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getX()
	                        - binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getWidth());
	                moving_rectangle_shift_1_duration =
	                        (long) (abs(moving_rectangle_shift_1 / moving_rectangle_full_shift)
	                                * moving_rectangle_full_shift_duration);

	                moving_rectangle_shift_2 = -binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getWidth();
	                moving_rectangle_shift_2_duration = (long) (abs(moving_rectangle_shift_2
	                        / moving_rectangle_full_shift) * moving_rectangle_full_shift_duration);

	                moving_rectangle_shift_3 = -binding.imageViewTargetRectangle.getX();
	                moving_rectangle_shift_3_duration = (long) (abs(moving_rectangle_shift_3
	                        / moving_rectangle_full_shift) * moving_rectangle_full_shift_duration);

	                ObjectAnimator translationAnimatorRight =
	                        ObjectAnimator.ofFloat(binding.movingRectangle, &quot;translationX&quot;,
	                                moving_rectangle_shift_1);
	                translationAnimatorRight.setDuration(moving_rectangle_shift_1_duration);

	                ObjectAnimator translationAnimatorMiddle =
	                        ObjectAnimator.ofFloat(binding.movingRectangle, &quot;translationX&quot;,
	                                moving_rectangle_shift_1 + moving_rectangle_shift_2);
	                translationAnimatorMiddle.setDuration(moving_rectangle_shift_2_duration);

	                ObjectAnimator translationAnimatorLeft =
	                        ObjectAnimator.ofFloat(binding.movingRectangle, &quot;translationX&quot;,
	                                moving_rectangle_full_shift);
	                translationAnimatorLeft.setDuration(moving_rectangle_shift_3_duration);
	                animatorSet.playSequentially(
	                        translationAnimatorRight,
	                        translationAnimatorMiddle,
	                        translationAnimatorLeft
	                );

	                // Must use a LinearInterpolator or there will be uneven movement.
	                animatorSet.setInterpolator(new LinearInterpolator());
	                animatorSet.addListener(new AnimatorListenerAdapter() {
	                    @Override
	                    public void onAnimationEnd(Animator animation) {
	                        super.onAnimationEnd(animation);
	                        showStatus(&quot;Total miss!&quot;);
	                    }
	                });
	                translationAnimatorMiddle.addUpdateListener(animation -&gt; {
	                    float animatedValue = (float) animation.getAnimatedValue();
	                    Log.d(&quot;Applog&quot;, String.format(&quot;transX = %f delta = %f frame #%d&quot;,
	                            animatedValue, animatedValue - lastTransX, ++frameCount));
	                    lastTransX = animatedValue;
	                });
	            }
	        });

	        return binding.getRoot();
	    }

	    @SuppressLint(&quot;ClickableViewAccessibility&quot;)
	    @Override
	    public boolean onTouch(View v, MotionEvent event) {
	        if (event.getAction() == MotionEvent.ACTION_DOWN) {
	            if (isAnimation2Running()) {
	                animatorSet.cancel();
	                showStatus(&quot;Hit!&quot;);
	            } else if (isAnimatorSetStarted()) {
	                animatorSet.cancel();
	                showStatus(&quot;Miss!&quot;);
	            } else {
	                showStatus(&quot;&quot;);
	                frameCount = 0;
	                lastTransX = 0;
	                animatorSet.start();
	            }
	        }
	        return false;
	    }

	    @Override
	    public void onDestroyView() {
	        super.onDestroyView();
	        binding = null;
	    }

	    private void showStatus(String text) {
	        binding.status.setText(text);
	    }

	    private boolean isAnimation2Running() {
	        return animatorSet.getChildAnimations().get(1).isRunning();
	    }

	    private boolean isAnimatorSetStarted() {
	        return animatorSet.isStarted();
	    }
