I&#39;d suggest a couple of things first:

* It would be good to format your code.
* It&#39;s generally a good idea to limit the code in your method to what its name suggests it should do. This is a broad guideline with exceptions of course, but here your `delete` method clearly adds nodes to your list.

Your problem here is as follows:

```java
while (temp!=null) {
    System.out.print(temp.data);
    temp=temp.next;
}
// At this stage, &quot;temp&quot; is null.
        
for (i=1;i&lt;n-1;i++) {
    // Side-node: this loop body will never run when called with n=2.
    temp=temp.next;
}

// Since &quot;temp&quot; is still null, using &quot;temp.next&quot;
// will throw a null pointer exception.
temp.next=temp.next.next;
```

To fix this you could:
* add your Nodes 4, 3 and 1 *outside* the delete loop;
  * firstly, simply because it makes more sense;
  * secondly, because you&#39;d start afresh at your &quot;delete&quot; loop with `Node temp=head;`
* you&#39;d still need to check whether `temp` or `temp.next` are `null` before trying to use `temp.next.next`. You&#39;d also need to test whether `temp` in your `(i=1;i&lt;n-1;i++)` loop (you could reach the end of the list before reaching `n`).

Depending on what you want your last `while` loop to do, it may have the same problems: it starts off with `temp` as it was left by the previous code. If you want it to print your new linked list, you&#39;ll need to reset `temp` to be `head`.

